Based on weekly data for past 10 years, the mean 2-week spread change has a mean of 0.21 bp, stdev of 24.4bp, max of 122.9bps and min of -120.2 bps. The current spread is 143.6 bps. To have the spread exceeding 2.3 (I'm reading % here), the change over the next 2 weeks will need to be 86 bps or more. The number of such occurrences over the past 520 2-week observations is 2. Normalising data yields Prob (Spread <2.3%) = 0.999798. Allowing 1% for spread between 2.3%~2.7%, in case of recurrence of maximum 2-week change of 122.9 bps, and a bit: 143.6 + 122.9 = 265 bps.

A year ago the Italian 10-year was 3.43% - yesterday it was at .865%. Charts indicate upward movement to maybe .90% The 10-year bund went from +.424% to -.545% over the same period.Charts indicate testing -.537 and falling back. .90 - (-.537) = 1.437% estimated spread by the time this question ends - far below the question's 2.30 benchmark. I never would have imagined the collapse of the Italian yield over this 12-month period like it has.

similar reasoning as @emil (e.g., brownian motion construct) except i did no math and generally just know from work experience that bond spreads do not move very much over 1 month. at this point, there just isn't enough time for the spread to move from 1.46 to 2.30... that sounds like a big jump to me.

The spread has collapsed to 157 bps at close today from 238 bps on Aug 10, and is now plateauing. The German 10-year is at -.544%, having risen from -.594% on Aug 11 and -.712% on Sep 2. The Italian 10-year is 1.026% from 1.736% in August 11 - so of late it seems the demand for Italian debt is driving down the spread. in the time that remains - such recent big moves may now settle into a trading range.

As of today, following another political crisis in Italy, the spread sits at around 2.00. In case of no elections, a new coalition government is likely to calm investors and bring the spread even lower. The worst case would be a new election in autumn. By the 20th October there would be much debate and uncertainty, but every party will play as much as possible to keep the spread below 3.00, aware of the political value given to the issue nowadays.

In order for the spread to increase meaningfully there needs to be increased probability of Italy either leaving the EU or breaking EU budget rules. The probability of either of these outcomes is low based on Italy's recent moves to appease the EU on the budget rules until 2020.

Generally speaking in an emergency people flee to the bund. But as the emergency passes they will run to something that offers a yield.

With the fall of the government, the risk premium when from 230 bps two weeks ago to 211 bps today Aug 20, recovering slightly from 204 bps last week. Italian yields on gov't 10-year bonds are in sharp decline, from over 3% in Nov 2018 to 1.34% presently. Normally I would have expected yields to rise, not fall, on national uncertainty. But EU QE and negative interest rates make the Italian bond attractive - an investor gets both positive yield and capital gain. And I think that's overriding anything on the political front - certainly between now and Oct 20.
If the italians don't no-conf their government this is a shoe in. The question now becomes.. will the italian govt last till 10/xx

I don;' know - in the search for positive yields, with the ECB actions to drop rates (if not outright QE) - which is to fall faster the bund or the Italian - and what will be the driver for each? The German 10-year has really been on a steep slide per the charts, currently yielding-.565%, from +.005% on May 1 - a 100X order of magnitude drop if my math is right? The Italian 10-year fell from +2.57% on May 1 to the present +1.538% - a "mere" 33% drop in yield. The spread was +2.58% on May 1 and is 2.13% 8-8-19. It seems the bund is falling faster than the Italian. Based on a -.90% guess for the bund in Oct and a +1%guess for the Italian - the spread would be barely 2%. Regardless if my back-of the envelope is correct/close---I see no evidence for a near-term rise in rates. And even that the pace of decrease decelerates - it just looks like a 2% spread, or thereabouts, for October.

I'll take the rogues view that nobody cares anymore if the Italians push their budget deficit past EU guidelines of 3% GDP. I have no math to back this - just a sense that I observe a willingness of Draghi (and successor) to go back to QE, and the trillions of now-negative yielding sovereign debt. That is big pressure onto the spread as interest rates return to being crushed. institutional money has to chase positive yield wherever they can find it - and either sign up for the vagaries of EM debt, or stay with the known-unknowns like Italian debt - which seems about right for the many. This lid on the spread, in the immediate term, considers both the possibility of larger-than-permitted fiscal deficits and the possible breakup of the coalition government, and the ascension of the League.

Risk assets react positively to perception of more central bank easing, Lagarde at ECB is perceived dovish. If the goldilocks scenario continues the odds of the left tail increase. By October, however, growth deterioration may become a negative too big to ignore and odds of an accident leading to spreads widening go up too. we have seen 150-200bps widening in 3-4 months before, so current 200bps could become 300-400bps spread.

Lot's of factors at play here. I think on balance, assuming no major macro events during the summer, their spread will go tighter over the next few months. Potential ECB stimulus, pick up vs Portugal and Spain and general hunt for yield will help with the spread tightening. Possible downsides that will cause higher spreads here is if the EDP discussion will not end well (potentially with sanctions) and if Salvini calls for an early election considering his success in the EU election. I see the risk of a downgrade from one of the rating agencies as fairly limited.
